<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-16T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-16T02:00:00-05:00" n="496" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d496">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/2217: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-16T15:00:00+08:00">December 16, 1937—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 16—2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1162. Referring to my 1156, December 15, 9 p.m.,<note n="44" xml:id="d496fn44">Not printed.</note> the First Secretary of the
                            Japanese Embassy informed this office this morning that according to
                            reports from the Japanese military in Nanking the 18 Americans who
                            remained in that city are well and uninjured and that the Embassy
                            buildings were not damaged.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>